# ADR: Phased Mobile UI Improvements

## Status
Complete

## Implementation Progress

| Phase | Description | Status |
|-------|-------------|--------|
| 1 | Navigation overhaul — bottom tab bar + sidebar drawer overlay | Complete |
| 2 | Responsive grid — dynamic column count, breakpoint dead-zone fix | Complete |
| 3 | Touch targets, lightbox mobile layout, modal sizing | Complete |
| 4 | Polish — safe areas, reduced motion, admin table cards | Complete |

---

## Context

### Background

The web UI was built desktop-first. The layout, navigation, and grid assumptions all stem from
a design where horizontal space is abundant and mouse interaction is precise. The result is an
app that is difficult to use on phones and tablets:

- The sidebar permanently occupies 48–256px of horizontal space on every screen size.
- There is a single layout breakpoint at 500px; screens between 500px and ~700px (phone
  landscape, small tablet) get the desktop justified-layout which is tuned for wide viewports.
- The mobile grid is hardcoded to 2 columns regardless of device width.
- Interactive elements (sidebar nav links, directory tree chevrons) are 28–32px — below the
  44px minimum touch target size recommended by Apple and Google.
- The Admin page renders data tables with fixed column widths that overflow on narrow screens.
- No safe-area insets are applied, so content renders under the iPhone home indicator.
- No `prefers-reduced-motion` support.

### Current layout structure

```
AppShell
├── <div class="flex h-screen overflow-hidden">
│   ├── <div class="w-12 | w-64">          ← always present, pushes content
│   │   └── Sidebar
│   └── <main class="flex-1 overflow-auto">
│       └── <Outlet />                      ← LibrariesPage | BrowsePage | AdminPage
```

On a 390px phone with the sidebar expanded: `390 - 256 = 134px` of usable content width.
On a 390px phone with the sidebar collapsed: `390 - 48 = 342px` of usable content width.
Neither state is acceptable for a primary browsing interface.

### What is NOT in scope

- Dark/light mode toggle — the app is always dark; this is a separate feature request.
- Authentication / login flows — Phase 5 per the main project plan.
- Offline / PWA support — not targeted.
- Native mobile apps (iOS / Android) — this ADR covers the web UI only.
- Responsive API pagination — the API returns the same page size regardless of client; no
  change needed to the server.
- Accessibility audit beyond touch targets — WCAG compliance is a separate workstream.
- Any changes to the Python API or CLI.

