## Phase 3 — Touch Targets, Lightbox, and Modal Sizing

**Goal**: All interactive elements meet the 44px minimum touch target size. The lightbox image
gets appropriate vertical space on mobile. Modals do not get squeezed on small phones.

### Touch targets

#### `src/ui/web/src/components/Sidebar.tsx`

Nav link items: change `py-2` → `py-3` (48px height, meets target).

```tsx
// Before
<Link className="... px-2 py-2 text-sm ...">

// After
<Link className="... px-2 py-3 text-sm ...">
```

Active/hover background styles are unchanged.

#### `src/ui/web/src/components/DirectoryTree.tsx`

Expand/collapse chevron buttons: change `h-7 w-6` → `h-10 w-10` with `p-2` to expand the
hit area without changing the visible icon size:

```tsx
// Before
<button type="button" className="flex h-7 w-6 shrink-0 items-center justify-center">
  <ChevronIcon className="h-3 w-3" />
</button>

// After
<button type="button" className="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center p-2">
  <ChevronIcon className="h-3 w-3" />
</button>
```

The visual chevron size is unchanged; only the tap target grows.

### Lightbox mobile layout

#### `src/ui/web/src/components/Lightbox.tsx`

**Image container minimum height**: On mobile the stacked layout (image above metadata) gives
the image too little vertical space when the metadata panel is tall. Add `min-h-[50vh]` to the
image container so it always occupies at least half the viewport height:

```tsx
// Before
<div className="flex flex-1 items-center justify-center p-4 lg:p-8">

// After
<div className="flex flex-1 items-center justify-center p-4 lg:p-8 min-h-[50vh] lg:min-h-0">
```

`lg:min-h-0` removes the constraint on desktop where the flex row layout already handles
proportions correctly.

**Navigation arrows**: Increase tap area on mobile by changing `p-4` → `p-5` and adding
`min-h-[44px] min-w-[44px]`:

```tsx
// Before
<button className="absolute left-0 top-1/2 ... p-4">
<button className="absolute right-0 top-1/2 ... p-4">

// After
<button className="absolute left-0 top-1/2 ... p-5 min-h-[44px] min-w-[44px]">
<button className="absolute right-0 top-1/2 ... p-5 min-h-[44px] min-w-[44px]">
```

**Metadata panel collapsible on mobile**: The metadata panel currently always stacks below the
image on mobile (correct direction), but it starts fully expanded. Add a `metaOpen` state
(default `true`) with a toggle button visible only on mobile (`md:hidden`). When `!metaOpen`
the panel collapses to just its header row (asset filename + toggle button) using
`max-h-[3rem] overflow-hidden` vs `max-h-none`. This preserves the full panel on desktop with
zero behavioral change above `md:`.

```tsx
const [metaOpen, setMetaOpen] = useState(true);

// Panel wrapper:
<div className={`
  w-full overflow-y-auto border-t border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/50 p-6
  lg:w-80 lg:border-l lg:border-t-0
  transition-[max-height] duration-200
  ${metaOpen ? "max-h-none" : "max-h-[3.5rem] overflow-hidden"} lg:max-h-none
`}>
  {/* Toggle button — mobile only */}
  <button
    className="flex w-full items-center justify-between md:hidden mb-4"
    onClick={() => setMetaOpen(o => !o)}
  >
    <span className="text-sm font-medium text-gray-300">Details</span>
    <ChevronUpIcon className={`h-4 w-4 transition-transform ${metaOpen ? "" : "rotate-180"}`} />
  </button>
  {/* ...existing metadata content... */}
</div>
```

### Modal sizing

#### `src/ui/web/src/components/Modal.tsx`

Replace `max-w-md` with a responsive width that respects small viewports:

```tsx
// Before
<div className="w-full max-w-md rounded-xl ...">

// After
<div className="w-[calc(100vw-2rem)] max-w-md rounded-xl ...">
```

Reduce padding on small screens:

```tsx
// Before
<div className="p-6">

// After
<div className="p-4 sm:p-6">
```

### Acceptance criteria

- All tap targets in Sidebar and DirectoryTree measure ≥ 44px in both dimensions (verify in
  browser devtools device mode).
- On a 390px phone, the lightbox image occupies at least 50% of the viewport height before
  metadata begins.
- The metadata panel can be collapsed and expanded via the Details toggle on mobile; on desktop
  the toggle button is invisible and the panel is always fully expanded.
- On a 320px viewport (SE-size phone), the modal does not overflow or clip its content.
- No visual regressions at `md:` and above.

