## Phase 4 — Polish: Safe Areas, Reduced Motion, Admin Table Cards

**Goal**: The app respects OS-level accessibility preferences and renders correctly on devices
with notches and home indicators. The Admin page is usable on mobile without horizontal
scrolling.

### Safe-area insets

Phase 1 adds `tailwindcss-safe-area` and applies `pb-safe` to the bottom nav. Phase 4 audits
the remaining surfaces:

- **Lightbox close button** (`absolute right-4 top-4`): add `mt-safe mr-safe` so it does not
  render under a Dynamic Island or notch in landscape.
- **Lightbox nav arrows** (`absolute left-0` / `right-0`): add `ml-safe` / `mr-safe`.
- **BrowsePage header**: add `pt-safe` if the header is ever positioned under the status bar
  (relevant when switching to a full-screen media view in the future).

These are utility class additions only — one to three characters per element.

### Reduced motion

Audit every `transition-*` and `animate-*` class in the codebase and prefix with
`motion-reduce:transition-none` / `motion-reduce:animate-none` where the animation is
decorative (not load-state indicators):

| Component | Class to guard |
|-----------|----------------|
| `AppShell.tsx` | `transition-all duration-200` (sidebar width) |
| `DrawerOverlay.tsx` | `transition-transform duration-200` (drawer slide) |
| `Lightbox.tsx` | metadata panel `transition-[max-height]` |
| `DirectoryTree.tsx` | any chevron rotation transitions |

Loading spinners (`animate-spin`) and skeleton pulses (`animate-pulse`) are functional
feedback — do not suppress them.

### Admin page: stacked card view on mobile

#### `src/ui/web/src/pages/AdminPage.tsx`

The workers/jobs table has 5–6 columns with fixed widths that overflow at 390px. Replace the
`<table>` with a responsive layout that renders as a table on `sm:` and above, and as stacked
cards on smaller screens.

Pattern: hide the `<thead>` and convert each `<tr>` into a card using CSS Grid with labeled
rows. This avoids duplicating the JSX — the label text lives in a `data-label` attribute and
is rendered via a CSS pseudo-element, or more simply, via an explicit label `<span>` that is
hidden on `sm:`:

```tsx
{/* Wrapper: scrollable table on sm+, card list on mobile */}
<div className="sm:overflow-x-auto">
  <table className="w-full">
    <thead className="hidden sm:table-header-group">
      {/* ...existing thead... */}
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {jobs.map(job => (
        <tr key={job.id}
            className="flex flex-col gap-1 border-b border-gray-800 py-3
                       sm:table-row sm:border-0 sm:py-0">
          <td className="sm:px-4 sm:py-2">
            <span className="text-xs text-gray-500 sm:hidden">Worker </span>
            <span className="font-mono text-xs text-gray-400 truncate">
              {job.worker_id ?? "—"}
            </span>
          </td>
          {/* ...remaining cells, same pattern... */}
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>
```

The `sm:table-row` Tailwind class restores standard table row rendering above the breakpoint.
The `<span className="text-xs text-gray-500 sm:hidden">` label spans are invisible on desktop.
No data or query logic changes.

**Browser caveat**: Switching a `<tr>` between `display: flex` (mobile) and `display: table-row`
(desktop) is broadly supported but can produce layout artifacts in Safari iOS — particularly if
any cell has `overflow: hidden` or explicit width constraints. Verify in Safari iOS during
implementation. If the flex/table toggle fights back, the fallback is a separate mobile-only
`<ul>` card list rendered alongside the `<table>` (each hidden via `sm:hidden` /
`hidden sm:block`) — more JSX but zero browser compatibility risk.

### Viewport meta verification

#### `src/ui/web/index.html`

Confirm the standard mobile viewport meta tag is present (it already exists as
`initial-scale=1.0`, which is equivalent to `initial-scale=1` — no change needed):

```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
```

Without this tag, mobile browsers render the page at a desktop-emulated width (~980px) and
scale it down, making all breakpoints useless. This is already correct; Phase 4 is a
verification step only.

### Acceptance criteria

- On an iPhone 14 Pro (has Dynamic Island): lightbox close button and nav arrows do not
  render behind the Dynamic Island cutout in landscape mode.
- With "Reduce Motion" enabled in iOS/macOS Accessibility settings: sidebar slide animation,
  drawer slide animation, and metadata panel height transition do not play.
- Loading spinners and skeleton pulses continue to animate in reduce-motion mode.
- Admin page on 390px phone: all job rows are readable as stacked cards with no horizontal
  overflow; on 640px+ the table layout is restored.
- `index.html` viewport meta tag confirmed present (already correct; no code change).

